richTextContent.insert: There is a general best practice that considers 3 seconds to be a maximum, acceptable time for a page to load.  The chart above will respond to selections made elsewhere on the dashboard, in order to help pin-point performance degraded or improvd at a point in time.  Note, the Distribution charts below don't respond to these selections based on the dynamic nature of bucketing EPTs.
Note: there is a minor issue with selections on the dashboard that prevent the above distribution charts from rendering if a date is selected on a timeline chart.

A scatter chart is a great way to asses several performance dimensions at once. Each bubble represent an object (or 'Page Entity Type').  The bottom axis is the average EPT, and the left axis is the number of page views. The size of the bubble relates to the number of users who viewed that object.
Any large bubbles on the top-right of the plot are the first priority and should be investigated to see what optimisations can be made.
When you identify an object with high EPT, click on the bubble and investigate the chart below...
Similar to the scatter chart above, each bubble relates to object

. Because different objects may have different page layouts in different apps, this chart shows the count of the number of components on the page (bubble size). By clicking on an object in the first chart, this second may help explain if a particular app or layout is contributing towards high average EPT.
Lightning Effective Page Time (EPT): Performance  Analysis

The above charts show the distribution of page performance, sorted by most-popular, not by EPT. Good performance analysis should focus on fixing what is most relevant to the business, and what can benefit the most number of users. While a larger segment of the chart by indicate worse performance, if it is further down the list (clockwise), it should be less of a priority. Blank "Page App" generally refers to Client apps, such as the standard Salesforce Mobile app.

Count of objects (standard and custom) viewed in a Lightning page.

"Lost Time" is the total amount of time spent waiting beyond the 3-second best-practice guideline.
e.g. if a page took 5 seconds to load 10 times (50s), Lost Time = (5-3)*10 = 20s.

richTextContent.insert: Variations in EPT may be down to the user's device, including operating system and browser.  If there aer variations specific to OS and Browser, investigate further by sub-grouping by OSversion  and Browser Version.
